 Policy 1: Informa Ɵon Security Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy deﬁnes Barclays’ approach to protec Ɵng informa Ɵon assets, ensuring conﬁden Ɵality, 
integrity, and availability (CIA). It applies to:  
 All employees, contractors, and third-party vendors.  
 All systems, applica Ɵons, and data owned or processed by Barclays globally.   
 All business units and subsidiaries.  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Audit Commi Ʃee reviews informa Ɵon security risks quarterly.   
 CISO Role:  Accountable for policy implementa Ɵon, repor Ɵng to the Group Risk Commi Ʃee.  
 Business Unit Responsibility:  Each unit must appoint an Informa Ɵon Security Oﬃcer (ISO).   
 Internal Audit:  Conducts annual reviews of compliance with this policy.  
3. Data Classiﬁca Ɵon & Handling   
 Classiﬁca Ɵon Levels:    
o Public: freely shareable.  
o Internal: restricted to Barclays staﬀ.  
o ConﬁdenƟal: sensiƟve customer or ﬁnancial data.   
o Highly Conﬁden Ɵal: strategic, regulatory, or M&A data.   
 Handling Rules:    
o ConﬁdenƟal/Highly Conﬁden Ɵal data must be encrypted at rest and in transit.   
o PrinƟng restricted; physical copies tracked.   
o Cloud storage requires Barclays-approved providers.  
o Data reten Ɵon aligned with regulatory requirements (minimum 7 years for ﬁnancial 
records).  
4. Access Control   
 Principle of Least Privilege:  Access granted only to perform job du Ɵes.  
 AuthenƟcaƟon: MFA mandatory for all privileged accounts.  
 Periodic Review:  Quarterly access recer ƟﬁcaƟon by managers.   
 Privileged Access Management (PAM):  All admin accounts monitored via PAM tools.  
 SegregaƟon of DuƟes: No single user may iniƟate and approve cri Ɵcal transac Ɵons.  
 
 5. Encryp Ɵon Standards   
 Data at Rest:  AES-256 encryp Ɵon.  
 Data in Transit:  TLS 1.3 or higher.  
 Key Management:  Keys rotated annually; stored in Hardware Security Modules (HSMs).  
 Mobile Devices:  Encrypted storage with Barclays-approved Mobile Device Management 
(MDM).  
6. Monitoring & Logging   
 Audit Logs:  Immutable, retained for 7 years.  
 SIEM Integra Ɵon: All criƟcal systems feed into Barclays’ Security Informa Ɵon and Event 
Management (SIEM).  
 AlerƟng: SOC monitors anomalies 24/7.  
 User AcƟvity Monitoring:  High-risk acƟviƟes ﬂagged for review.   
7. Employee Responsibili Ɵes  
 Training: Annual mandatory training with phishing simula Ɵons.  
 ReporƟng: Employees must report suspected breaches within 1 hour.  
 Acceptable Use:  Personal devices allowed only under BYOD policy with MDM controls.  
 Password Policy:  Minimum 14 characters, rotated every 90 days.  
8. Compliance & Regula Ɵon  
 GDPR & UK Data Protec Ɵon Act: Full compliance with data subject rights.  
 FCA/PRA Requirements:  Alignment with opera Ɵonal resilience frameworks.   
 NIS2 Direc Ɵve (EU): Applies to European opera Ɵons.  
 PCI-DSS: Compliance for payment card data.  
9. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
 Audit: Internal Audit reviews compliance annually.  
 ConƟnuous Improvement:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new threats.  
  
  
  
  
  
  Policy 2: Cybersecurity Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy  establishes  Barclays’ approach to managing cybersecurity risks, protec Ɵng customer and 
corporate data, and ensuring opera Ɵonal resilience against evolving threats. It applies to:   
 All Barclays employees, contractors, and third-party vendors.   
 All IT systems, applica Ɵons, and networks globally.   
 All business units and subsidiaries, including joint ventures.   
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Risk Commi Ʃee and Audit Commi Ʃee review cyber risk quarterly.   
 Chief Informa Ɵon Security Oﬃcer (CISO):  Accountable for cyber strategy, repor Ɵng to the 
Group Risk Commi Ʃee.  
 Cybersecurity Steering Commi Ʃee: Cross-func Ɵonal body overseeing implementa Ɵon, 
chaired by the CISO.   
 Internal Audit:  Conducts independent reviews of cyber resilience annually.   
  
3. Threat Detec Ɵon & Monitoring   
 Security Opera Ɵons Centre (SOC):  Operates 24/7 with global coverage.   
 SIEM Integra Ɵon: All criƟcal systems feed into Barclays’ Security Informa Ɵon and Event 
Management (SIEM).   
 Automated Threat Detec Ɵon: AI-driven analy Ɵcs to idenƟfy anomalies, phishing a Ʃempts, 
and malware.   
 Threat Intelligence:  Barclays subscribes to global intelligence feeds (FS-ISAC, NCSC UK).   
 ConƟnuous Monitoring:  Real-Ɵme monitoring of endpoints, servers, and cloud 
environments.   
  
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
4. Incident Response & Escala Ɵon  
 Incident Response Plan (IRP):  Deﬁnes roles, responsibili Ɵes, and escala Ɵon paths.   
 Response Time Targets:    
o DetecƟon within 15 minutes.   
o Containment within 1 hour.   
o Recovery within 24 hours  for criƟcal systems.   
 EscalaƟon Protocols:    
o Level 1: Local IT team.   
o Level 2: SOC escala Ɵon.  
o Level 3: Group CISO and Board  noƟﬁcaƟon.  
 Post-Incident Review:  Root cause analysis and lessons learned documented within 7 days.   
  
5. Penetra Ɵon TesƟng & Vulnerability Management   
 Red-Team Exercises:  Annual penetra Ɵon tests simula Ɵng real-world a Ʃacks.  
 Vulnerability Scans:  Conducted quarterly across all systems.   
 Patch Management:    
o CriƟcal patches applied within  48 hours.   
o High-risk patches within 7 days.   
o Medium-risk patches within  30 days.  
 ReporƟng: Monthly vulnerability reports  submiƩed to the Risk Commi Ʃee.  
  
6. Third-Party & Supply Chain Risk   
 Vendor Due Diligence:  All vendors must  comply with  Barclays’ security standards.   
 Contractual Obliga Ɵons: Security clauses embedded in all contracts.   
 ConƟnuous Monitoring:  Vendors subject to ongoing risk assessments.   
 Cloud Providers:  Must meet Barclays’ encryp Ɵon and resilience standards.   
  
 
 
 
 
7. AI & Emerging Technology Risks   
 AI Risk Management:  Barclays monitors AI-driven fraud and cyber threats.   
 Ethical AI Use:  AI systems must  comply with  Barclays’ Code of Conduct.   
 Bias & Transparency:  AI models  reviewed for  bias and explainability.   
 Emerging Threats:  Policies updated annually to address quantum compu Ɵng, deepfakes, and 
advanced persistent threats (APTs).   
  
8. Employee Awareness & Training   
 Mandatory Training:  Annual cybersecurity awareness training for all employees.   
 Phishing Simula Ɵons: Quarterly exercises to test employee resilience.   
 Role-Speciﬁc Training:  Enhanced training for privileged users and developers.   
 ReporƟng Culture:  Employees encouraged to report suspicious ac Ɵvity without fear of 
reprisal.  
  
9. Compliance & Regula Ɵon  
 GDPR & UK Data Protec Ɵon Act: Full compliance with data protec Ɵon requirements.   
 FCA/PRA Opera Ɵonal Resilience:  Cybersecurity integrated into resilience frameworks.   
 NIS2 Direc Ɵve (EU): Applies to European opera Ɵons.  
 ISO 27001:  Barclays aligns with  internaƟonal informa Ɵon security standards.   
  
10. Metrics & KPIs   
 Incident Response Time:  Average Ɵme to detect and  contain incidents.   
 Patch Compliance Rate:  Percentage of systems patched within required Ɵmelines.  
 Phishing Resilience Score:  Percentage of employees passing phishing simula Ɵons.  
 Vendor Compliance Rate:  Percentage of vendors mee Ɵng Barclays’ security standards.   
  
11. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
 Audit: Internal Audit reviews compliance annually.   
 ConƟnuous Improvement:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new threats.   
  
 
Policy 3: IT Opera Ɵons & Resilience Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy deﬁnes Barclays’ approach to ensuring IT opera Ɵonal resilience, business con Ɵnuity, and 
disaster recovery. It applies to:   
 All Barclays IT systems, applica Ɵons, and infrastructure globally.   
 All employees, contractors, and third-party service providers.   
 All business units and subsidiaries, including joint ventures.   
The objecƟve is to ensure that Barclays can withstand, respond to, and recover from opera Ɵonal 
disrupƟons while  maintaining  criƟcal services for customers, regulators, and stakeholders.   
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Risk Commi Ʃee and Audit Commi Ʃee oversee resilience planning.   
 Chief Opera Ɵng Oﬃcer (COO):  Accountable for IT opera Ɵons and resilience strategy.   
 Resilience Steering Commi Ʃee: Cross-func Ɵonal body responsible for resilience tes Ɵng and 
reporƟng.  
 Internal Audit:  Conducts annual reviews of resilience controls and recovery capabili Ɵes.  
  
3. Business Con Ɵnuity Management (BCM)   
 CriƟcal Services Iden ƟﬁcaƟon: Barclays idenƟﬁes criƟcal services (payments, trading, 
customer access) and  maps dependencies.   
 Recovery Objec Ɵves:   
o Recovery Time Objec Ɵve (RTO): ≤ 4 hours for cri Ɵcal services.   
o Recovery Point Objec Ɵve (RPO): ≤ 15 minutes for cri Ɵcal data.  
 ConƟnuity Plans:  Each business unit  maintains  documented con Ɵnuity plans.   
 TesƟng: Annual con Ɵnuity exercises across all regions.   
  
 
 
 
 
 
 
4. Disaster Recovery (DR)   
 Data Centres: Barclays operates redundant data  centres with geographic separa Ɵon.  
 Cloud Resilience:  Hybrid cloud adop Ɵon with mul Ɵ-region failover.   
 Backup Strategy:    
o Daily backups for cri Ɵcal systems.   
o Weekly full backups  retained for 12 months.   
o Oﬀsite storage for disaster scenarios.   
 DR Drills:  Semi-annual disaster recovery drills simula Ɵng cybera Ʃacks, natural disasters, and 
system failures.   
  
5. Change Management   
 Approval Process:  All IT changes require documented approval and rollback plans.   
 SegregaƟon of DuƟes: Developers cannot deploy directly to produc Ɵon.  
 Audit Trails:  All changes logged and  retained for 7 years.   
 Emergency Changes:  Allowed only with CISO/COO approval, documented post-
implementa Ɵon.  
  
6. Cloud Security & Resilience   
 Cloud Adop Ɵon: Barclays uses hybrid cloud with strict iden Ɵty and access management.   
 Resilience Standards:  Cloud providers must meet Barclays’ encryp Ɵon and failover 
requirements.   
 Monitoring:  ConƟnuous monitoring of cloud workloads.   
 Exit Strategy:  Documented plans for cloud provider exit or migra Ɵon.  
  
7. Resilience Tes Ɵng  
 Scenario Tes Ɵng: Barclays conducts resilience tests for cybera Ʃacks, pandemics, and 
geopoliƟcal disrup Ɵons.  
 Tabletop Exercises:  Quarterly exercises with senior management.   
 Live Simula Ɵons: Annual live simula Ɵons involving IT, opera Ɵons, and business units.   
 Metrics: Test results documented and reported to the Board.   
  
 
8. OperaƟonal KPIs   
 System Up Ɵme: ≥ 99.95% for cri Ɵcal systems.   
 Incident Response Time:  ≤ 1 hour for cri Ɵcal incidents.   
 Patch Compliance Rate:  ≥ 95% within required Ɵmelines.  
 Resilience Test Pass Rate:  ≥ 90% across all scenarios.   
  
9. Third-Party & Outsourcing Risk   
 Vendor Resilience Standards:  Vendors must  demonstrate  resilience capabili Ɵes.  
 Contractual Obliga Ɵons: SLAs must include resilience metrics.   
 Monitoring:  ConƟnuous vendor risk assessments.   
 Exit Planning:  Documented con Ɵngency plans for vendor failure.   
  
10. Compliance & Regula Ɵon  
 FCA/PRA Opera Ɵonal Resilience Framework:  Full compliance with UK regulatory 
requirements.   
 GDPR & Data Protec Ɵon Act: Ensures data recovery aligns with privacy obliga Ɵons.  
 Basel Commi Ʃee Principles:  Alignment with interna Ɵonal banking resilience standards.   
 NIS2 Direc Ɵve (EU): Applies to European opera Ɵons.  
  
11. ConƟnuous Improvement   
 Annual Review:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new threats and regulatory changes.   
 Lessons Learned:  Post-incident reviews feed into resilience improvements.   
 InnovaƟon: AdopƟon of emerging technologies (AI, automa Ɵon) to enhance resilience.   
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
Policy 4: Data Privacy & Compliance Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy  establishes  Barclays’ approach to protec Ɵng customer and employee personal data, 
ensuring compliance with global privacy regula Ɵons, and maintaining  trust with stakeholders. It 
applies to:   
 All Barclays employees, contractors, and third-party vendors.   
 All systems, applica Ɵons, and processes handling personal or sensi Ɵve data.  
 All business units and subsidiaries globally.   
The objecƟve is to ensure lawful, fair, and transparent processing of personal data, aligned 
with GDPR, UK Data Protec Ɵon Act, and other applicable regula Ɵons.  
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Audit Commi Ʃee and Risk Commi Ʃee oversee data privacy risks.   
 Data Protec Ɵon Oﬃcer (DPO):  Accountable for compliance with privacy regula Ɵons, 
reporƟng to the Group Risk Commi Ʃee.  
 Business Unit Responsibility:  Each unit must appoint a Privacy Champion to oversee local 
compliance.   
 Internal Audit:  Conducts annual reviews of privacy controls and compliance.   
  
3. Data Collec Ɵon & Processing   
 Lawful Basis:  Data collected only under lawful bases (consent, contract, legal obliga Ɵon, 
legiƟmate interest).   
 Transparency:  Customers informed via privacy no Ɵces about data usage.   
 Purpose Limita Ɵon: Data processed only for speciﬁed, explicit, and legi Ɵmate purposes.   
 Data Minimiza Ɵon: Only necessary data collected and  retained.  
4. Data Subject Rights   
Barclays ensures compliance with GDPR and UK Data Protec Ɵon Act by enabling:   
 Right of Access:  Customers can request copies of their personal data.   
 Right to Rec ƟﬁcaƟon: Inaccurate data corrected promptly.   
 Right to Erasure (“Right to be Forgo Ʃen”): Data deleted upon valid request.   
 Right to Restrict Processing:  Customers can limit how their data is used.   
 Right to Data Portability:  Customers can request transfer of their data to another provider.   
 Right to Object:  Customers can object to processing for marke Ɵng or proﬁling.   
5. Data Security & Protec Ɵon  
 EncrypƟon: All personal data encrypted at rest (AES-256) and in transit (TLS 1.3).   
 Access Controls:  Role-based access with MFA.   
 Audit Logging:  Immutable logs  retained for 7 years.   
 Data Masking:  SensiƟve data masked in non-produc Ɵon environments.   
 Anonymiza Ɵon: Personal data  anonymized  when used for analy Ɵcs.  
  
6. Data Reten Ɵon & Disposal   
 RetenƟon Periods:    
o Customer  ﬁnancial records: minimum 7 years.   
o HR records: minimum 6  years post-employment.   
o MarkeƟng data: maximum 2 years  unless renewed consent.   
 Secure Disposal:  Data deleted using industry-standard secure wipe methods.   
 Archiving:  Archived data encrypted and access restricted.   
  
7. Third-Party & Vendor Compliance   
 Vendor Due Diligence:  Vendors must  comply with  Barclays’ privacy standards.   
 Data Processing Agreements (DPAs):  Mandatory for all vendors handling personal data.   
 Monitoring:  Vendors subject to ongoing compliance reviews.   
 Cross-Border Transfers:  Data transferred outside the UK/EU only with adequate safeguards 
(e.g., Standard Contractual Clauses).   
  
8. Employee Responsibili Ɵes  
 Training: Annual mandatory privacy training.   
 ReporƟng: Employees must report suspected data breaches within 1 hour.   
 Acceptable Use:  Personal data must not be stored on personal devices unless encrypted and 
approved.   
 ConﬁdenƟality Agreements:  All employees must sign conﬁden Ɵality agreements.   
  
 
 
 
9. Breach Management   
 Incident Response:  Data breaches reported to the DPO within 24 hours.   
 Regulatory No ƟﬁcaƟon: ICO and other regulators no Ɵﬁed within  72 hours if required.  
 Customer No ƟﬁcaƟon: Customers informed promptly if their data is  impacted.   
 Post-Incident Review:  Root cause analysis conducted within 7 days.   
  
10. Compliance & Regula Ɵon  
 GDPR: Full compliance with  EU General Data Protec Ɵon Regula Ɵon.  
 UK Data Protec Ɵon Act 2018:  Compliance across UK opera Ɵons.  
 FCA/PRA Requirements:  Privacy integrated into opera Ɵonal resilience frameworks.   
 NIS2 Direc Ɵve (EU): Applies to European opera Ɵons.  
 ISO 27701:  Alignment with interna Ɵonal privacy management standards.   
  
11. Metrics & KPIs   
 Data Breach Response Time:  ≤ 72 hours for regulatory no ƟﬁcaƟon.  
 Training Comple Ɵon Rate: ≥ 95% of employees annually.   
 Vendor Compliance Rate:  ≥ 90% of vendors  meeƟng Barclays’ privacy standards.   
 Data Subject Request Fulﬁllment:  ≥ 95% requests fulﬁlled within statutory Ɵmelines.  
  
12. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
 Audit: Internal Audit reviews compliance annually.   
 ConƟnuous Improvement:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new regula Ɵons and threats.   
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
Policy 5: Employee & Insider Risk Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy  establishes  Barclays’ approach to managing insider risk, ensuring employees and 
contractors act responsibly, and protec Ɵng the organiza Ɵon against internal threats. It applies to:   
 All Barclays employees, contractors, and third-party vendors with system or data access.   
 All business units and subsidiaries globally.   
 All systems, applica Ɵons, and processes where insider ac Ɵvity could  impact conﬁdenƟality, 
integrity, or availability.   
The objecƟve is to miƟgate risks arising from human error, negligence, or malicious insider ac Ɵvity 
while fostering a culture of accountability and trust.   
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Risk Commi Ʃee and Audit Commi Ʃee oversee insider risk 
management.   
 Chief Human Resources Oﬃcer (CHRO):  Accountable for employee conduct and insider risk 
programs.   
 Chief Informa Ɵon Security Oﬃcer (CISO):  Accountable for monitoring insider ac Ɵvity and 
reporƟng to the Group Risk Commi Ʃee.  
 Insider Risk Management Team:  Cross-func Ɵonal body including HR, Legal, Compliance, and 
IT Security.   
 Internal Audit:  Conducts annual reviews of insider risk controls.   
  
3. Employee Onboarding & Screening   
 Background Checks:  Mandatory for all new hires, including criminal, ﬁnancial, and reference 
checks.  
 Access Provisioning:  Access granted only a Ōer comple Ɵon of onboarding and training.   
 ConﬁdenƟality Agreements:  All employees must sign conﬁden Ɵality agreements before 
system access.   
 Role-Based Access:  Access aligned with job responsibili Ɵes, reviewed quarterly.   
  
 
 
 
 
4. Acceptable Use Policy   
 System Usage:  Employees must use Barclays systems only for authorized business purposes.   
 Personal Devices (BYOD):  Allowed only under Mobile Device Management (MDM) controls.   
 Email & Internet Use:  Restricted to professional ac ƟviƟes; monitoring in place.   
 Prohibited Ac ƟviƟes: Unauthorized downloads, use of unapproved cloud services, and data 
exﬁltraƟon.  
  
5. Monitoring & Detec Ɵon  
 User AcƟvity Monitoring:  High-risk ac ƟviƟes ﬂagged for review (e.g., mass downloads, 
unusual access Ɵmes).  
 Behavioral Analy Ɵcs: AI-driven monitoring of anomalous employee behavior.   
 Privileged User Monitoring:  Enhanced monitoring for administrators and developers.   
 Audit Logging:  Immutable logs  retained for 7 years.   
  
6. Training & Awareness   
 Mandatory Training:  Annual insider risk and cybersecurity awareness training.   
 Phishing Simula Ɵons: Quarterly exercises to test employee resilience.   
 Role-Speciﬁc Training:  Enhanced training for privileged users and developers.   
 Culture of Responsibility:  Employees encouraged to report suspicious ac Ɵvity without fear 
of reprisal.   
  
7. Incident Response & Escala Ɵon  
 Insider Threat Response Plan:  Deﬁnes roles, responsibili Ɵes, and escala Ɵon paths.   
 EscalaƟon Protocols:    
o Level 1: Local HR/IT team.   
o Level 2: Insider Risk Management Team.   
o Level 3: Group CISO and Board  noƟﬁcaƟon.  
 Post-Incident Review:  Root cause analysis and lessons learned documented within 7 days.   
 Disciplinary Ac Ɵon: May include suspension, termina Ɵon, or legal proceedings.   
  
 
 
8. Whistleblowing & Repor Ɵng  
 Whistleblowing Hotline:  Anonymous repor Ɵng channel available globally.   
 ProtecƟon: Whistleblowers protected against retalia Ɵon.  
 InvesƟgaƟon: All reports inves Ɵgated promptly by HR and Compliance.   
 Transparency:  Outcomes reported to the Audit Commi Ʃee.  
  
9. Third-Party & Contractor Risk   
 Vendor Screening:  Contractors subject to background checks and access restric Ɵons.  
 Access Controls:  Contractors granted Ɵme-bound, role-based access.   
 Monitoring:  Contractor ac Ɵvity monitored  conƟnuously.  
 Exit Procedures:  Contractor access revoked  immediately  upon contract termina Ɵon.  
  
10. Compliance & Regula Ɵon  
 GDPR & UK Data Protec Ɵon Act: Insider monitoring aligned with privacy obliga Ɵons.  
 FCA/PRA Requirements:  Insider risk integrated into opera Ɵonal resilience frameworks.   
 Employment Law:  Compliance with local labor laws across  jurisdicƟons.  
 ISO 27001:  Alignment with interna Ɵonal informa Ɵon security standards.   
  
11. Metrics & KPIs   
 Training Comple Ɵon Rate: ≥ 95% of employees annually.   
 Incident Response Time:  ≤ 24 hours for insider incidents.   
 Privileged Access Review Rate:  100% quarterly.   
 Whistleblowing Case Resolu Ɵon: ≥ 90% resolved within statutory Ɵmelines.  
  
12. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
