Policy 6: Emerging Technology & AI Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy  establishes  Barclays’ approach to adop Ɵng, governing, and securing emerging 
technologies, with a par Ɵcular focus on Ar Ɵﬁcial Intelligence (AI). It applies to:   
 All Barclays employees, contractors, and third-party vendors  involved in technology 
development, deployment, or oversight.   
 All AI systems, machine learning models, and emerging technologies (cloud, blockchain, 
quantum compu Ɵng, etc.) used within Barclays.   
 All business units and subsidiaries globally.   
The objecƟve is to ensure that emerging technologies are deployed responsibly, ethically, securely, 
and in compliance with regulatory requirements.   
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Technology Commi Ʃee and Risk Commi Ʃee oversee emerging 
technology adop Ɵon.  
 Chief Technology Oﬃcer (CTO):  Accountable for emerging technology strategy.   
 Chief Informa Ɵon Security Oﬃcer (CISO):  Accountable for security risks associated with  new 
technologies.   
 AI Governance Council:  Cross-func Ɵonal body including Risk, Compliance, Legal, and 
Technology teams.   
 Internal Audit:  Conducts annual reviews of AI and emerging technology governance.   
  
3. AI Governance Framework   
 Ethical Principles:  AI systems must be fair, transparent, accountable, and aligned with 
Barclays’ Code of Conduct.   
 Bias Monitoring:  AI models tested regularly for bias and discriminatory outcomes.   
 Explainability:  AI decisions must be  explainable  to regulators, customers, and internal 
stakeholders.   
 Human Oversight:  CriƟcal AI decisions (e.g., credit scoring, fraud detec Ɵon) require human 
validaƟon.  
 Lifecycle Management:  AI models documented, version-controlled, and subject to periodic 
review.  
  
 
 
4. Security & Risk Management   
 AI-Speciﬁc Threats:  Monitoring for  adversarial a Ʃacks, model poisoning, and deepfake 
fraud.  
 Data Security:  Training data must be anonymized, encrypted, and sourced responsibly.   
 Access Controls:  Role-based access to AI models and datasets.   
 Incident Response:  AI-related incidents escalated through Barclays’ SOC and IRP.   
 Third-Party Risk:  Vendors providing AI solu Ɵons must comply with  Barclays’ security 
standards.   
  
5. Emerging Technology Adop Ɵon  
 Cloud Compu Ɵng: Hybrid cloud adop Ɵon with strict iden Ɵty and access management.   
 Blockchain:  Used only for approved ﬁnancial services with regulatory compliance.   
 Quantum Compu Ɵng: Research monitored for  potenƟal cryptographic risks.   
 AutomaƟon & Robo Ɵcs: Deployed with safeguards to prevent opera Ɵonal disrup Ɵon.  
 InnovaƟon Labs: Emerging technologies tested in controlled environments before 
producƟon deployment.   
  
6. Regulatory Compliance   
 GDPR & UK Data Protec Ɵon Act: AI systems must  comply with  data protec Ɵon 
requirements.   
 FCA/PRA Requirements:  Emerging technologies integrated into opera Ɵonal resilience 
frameworks.   
 EU AI Act:  Compliance with European AI regula Ɵons.  
 ISO/IEC 23894:  Alignment with interna Ɵonal AI risk management standards.   
  
7. Employee Awareness & Training   
 Mandatory Training:  Annual training on AI ethics and emerging technology risks.   
 Specialist Training:  Advanced training for developers, data scien Ɵsts, and risk managers.   
 Awareness Campaigns:  Regular updates on emerging threats (e.g., deepfakes, quantum 
risks).  
 ReporƟng Culture:  Employees encouraged to report concerns about AI or emerging 
technology misuse.   
  
8. Metrics & KPIs   
 AI Model Review Rate:  ≥ 95% of models reviewed annually.   
 Bias Detec Ɵon Rate: ≥ 90% of models tested for bias.   
 Vendor Compliance Rate:  ≥ 90% of vendors  meeƟng Barclays’ AI standards.   
 Training Comple Ɵon Rate: ≥ 95% of employees annually.   
  
9. ConƟnuous Improvement   
 Annual Review:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect  new technologies  and regulatory 
changes.  
 Lessons Learned:  Post-incident reviews feed into AI governance improvements.   
 InnovaƟon: AdopƟon of emerging technologies aligned with Barclays’ strategic  objecƟves.  
  
10. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
 Audit: Internal Audit reviews compliance annually.   
 ConƟnuous Improvement:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new threats and opportuni Ɵes.  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
Policy 7: Audit & Con Ɵnuous Improvement Policy   
1. Purpose & Scope   
This policy  establishes  Barclays’ approach to audi Ɵng IT and cybersecurity controls, monitoring 
compliance, and driving con Ɵnuous improvement across technology and risk management func Ɵons. 
It applies to:   
 All Barclays IT systems, applica Ɵons, and infrastructure globally.   
 All employees, contractors, and third-party vendors.   
 All business units and subsidiaries, including joint ventures.   
The objecƟve is to ensure that IT and cybersecurity prac Ɵces remain eﬀecƟve, resilient, and aligned 
with regulatory requirements and industry best prac Ɵces.  
  
2. Governance & Accountability   
 Board Oversight:  The Audit Commi Ʃee and Risk Commi Ʃee oversee IT audit and con Ɵnuous 
improvement ac ƟviƟes.  
 Chief Audit Execu Ɵve (CAE): Accountable for internal audit strategy and repor Ɵng.  
 Chief Informa Ɵon Security Oﬃcer (CISO):  Accountable for cybersecurity audit readiness and 
remediaƟon.  
 ConƟnuous Improvement Council:  Cross-func Ɵonal body including Audit, Risk, Compliance, 
and Technology teams.   
 External Assurance:  Independent external auditors engaged annually to  validate IT and cyber 
resilience.   
  
3. Audit Framework   
 Internal Audit:  Annual audits of IT opera Ɵons, cybersecurity, and data privacy controls.   
 Risk-Based Approach:  Audit priori Ɵes determined  by risk assessments and regulatory 
requirements.   
 Control Tes Ɵng: Key controls tested for design and opera Ɵng eﬀecƟveness.  
 Audit Trails:  All IT changes, incidents, and access logs  retained for 7 years.   
 ReporƟng: Audit ﬁndings reported to the Audit Commi Ʃee and Board.   
  
 
 
 
 
4. ConƟnuous Monitoring   
 Key Risk Indicators (KRIs):  Deﬁned for cyber incidents, system down Ɵme, and vendor 
compliance.   
 Key Performance Indicators (KPIs):    
o Incident response Ɵme.  
o Patch compliance  rate.  
o Training comple Ɵon rate.  
o Vendor compliance  rate.  
 Dashboards:  Real-Ɵme dashboards provided to senior management.   
 Automated Alerts:  SOC generates alerts for devia Ɵons from resilience thresholds.   
  
5. ConƟnuous Improvement Cycle   
 Plan: IdenƟfy risks, set objecƟves, and deﬁne improvement ini ƟaƟves.  
 Do: Implement controls, training, and technology enhancements.   
 Check: Audit and  monitor performance against KPIs.   
 Act: Remediate gaps, update policies, and enhance resilience.   
 Annual Review:  Policies updated annually to reﬂect new threats and regulatory changes.   
  
6. Incident & Breach Reviews   
 Post-Incident Analysis:  Root cause analysis conducted within 7 days of major incidents.   
 Lessons Learned:  Incorporated into updated controls and training programs.   
 Board Repor Ɵng: Signiﬁcant incidents reported to the Board with remedia Ɵon plans.  
 Regulatory Engagement:  Regulators informed of material incidents and correc Ɵve acƟons.  
  
7. Vendor & Third-Party Assurance   
 Vendor Audits:  Annual audits of cri Ɵcal vendors’ IT and cybersecurity prac Ɵces.  
 Contractual Obliga Ɵons: Vendors required to provide audit rights and compliance evidence.   
 ConƟnuous Monitoring:  Vendor compliance tracked via dashboards.   
 Exit Strategy:  ConƟngency plans for vendor failure or non-compliance.   
  
 
8. Regulatory Compliance   
 FCA/PRA Requirements:  Audit and improvement aligned with UK opera Ɵonal resilience 
frameworks.   
 GDPR & UK Data Protec Ɵon Act: Privacy audits conducted annually.   
 NIS2 Direc Ɵve (EU): Applies to European opera Ɵons.  
 ISO 27001 & ISO 27701:  Alignment with interna Ɵonal informa Ɵon security and privacy 
standards.   
  
9. Employee Engagement   
 Training: Annual audit awareness training for employees.   
 Feedback Mechanisms:  Employees encouraged to suggest improvements.   
 Whistleblowing:  Anonymous repor Ɵng channels for audit or compliance concerns.   
 RecogniƟon: Employees recognized for contribu Ɵons to con Ɵnuous improvement.   
  
10. Metrics & KPIs   
 Audit Comple Ɵon Rate: ≥ 95% of planned audits annually.   
 RemediaƟon Closure Rate:  ≥ 90% of audit ﬁndings closed within agreed Ɵmelines.  
 ConƟnuous Improvement Ini ƟaƟves: ≥ 80% completed annually.   
 Vendor Audit Compliance Rate:  ≥ 90% of vendors audited successfully.   
  
11. Enforcement   
 ViolaƟons: May result in disciplinary ac Ɵon, up to termina Ɵon.  
 Audit: Internal Audit reviews compliance annually.   
 ConƟnuous Improvement:  Policy updated annually to reﬂect new threats and opportuni Ɵes.  
  
  
 
